## 13. Force majeure

Neither Party will be liable for a failure or delay in performing their obligations where that failure or delay is caused by events beyond their reasonable control.

Force majeure events may include:

1. natural disasters;
2. extreme weather;
3. fire, flood, storm or earthquake;
4. war, terrorism, civil unrest or public emergency;
5. government restrictions, public health orders or border closures;
6. venue closure outside the control of the Parties;
7. epidemic, pandemic or public health emergency;
8. transport shutdowns or major travel disruptions;
9. serious illness, injury or incapacity; or
10. any other event beyond the reasonable control of the affected Party.

If a force majeure event affects the event or the Artist’s ability to perform, the Parties will first use reasonable efforts to reschedule or agree an alternative arrangement.

If the event cannot reasonably be rescheduled, or the Artist is unavailable for the rescheduled date, the Parties will discuss a fair outcome having regard to:

1. work already performed;
2. costs already incurred;
3. the Artist’s reserved availability;
4. any amounts recoverable by the Artist from suppliers or insurers; and
5. the Client’s rights under applicable law.

Nothing in this clause excludes or limits any non-excludable rights under the Australian Consumer Law.

