## 21. Copyright, moral rights and image use

The Parties acknowledge that the artwork may be a commissioned portrait for a private or domestic purpose. To the extent that section 35(5) of the Copyright Act 1968 applies, copyright in the finished commissioned portrait may vest in the Client.

The Artist retains all moral rights in the artwork, including the right to be attributed as the creator, the right against false attribution and the right of integrity.

The Client must not:

1. falsely attribute the artwork to another person;
2. remove or obscure the Artist’s signature;
3. alter, distort, mutilate or treat the artwork in a way that is prejudicial to the Artist’s honour or reputation;
4. use the artwork or images of the artwork in a derogatory, misleading, unlawful or offensive way;
5. use the artwork commercially without the Artist’s prior written consent;
6. sell reproductions, prints, merchandise, NFTs or digital products based on the artwork without the Artist’s prior written consent; or
7. use the artwork to train, prompt or generate AI outputs without the Artist’s prior written consent.

The Artist may restrain use of the artwork outside the private or domestic purpose for which it was commissioned, to the extent permitted by law.

